segments.text: We're in the sixth floor of the library, and I have the joy of chatting with John Thomas about his A&M experiences, just so recent, a young man like him.
John, try your mic and see how it works.
Well, we'll see if it picks up.
I'll bet it does.
John, to begin with, to introduce yourself to a reader or a listener in future years,
Describe family background, where you grew up, where you went to high school.
Tell about yourself before coming to A&M.
Well, I was born in Pampa, Texas.
better known for the home of Randy Mattson.
Dad was working in the oil fields then.
He was a roommate of Earl Rudders at Tarleton.
When Earl left Tarleton, he came to A&M, and Dad went to the oil fields for 10 years.
That was right at the tail end of the Depression.
He spent 10 years there and then came back to A&M.
I was about three when he came back to school here.
He went as county extension agent, assistant agent at Naples and then in February of 42 moved to Wellington, Collingsworth County as county agent.
Was there 17 years.

was in the middle of the first grade when we got to wellington and graduated high school there how big wellington and wellington had about 33 3400 population when we got there it was a ranching and farming community right against oklahoma there in the early 50s in my high school years i got out in 55
and came to A&M but during the 50s that drought and population had reached about 51, 5,200 county populations about 25,000 and we lived on a farm there.
I grew up in 4-H club work and A&M was
Probably because of my interest in ag and particular interest in entomology as a result of having kept honeybees for a 4-H club project.
I was aware that A&M was the only place you could go and major in entomology and a strong ag school, and we had come to 4-H Roundup.
Back then, coming to College Station was about like going to China.
It was a long way away.
And describe one of those trips.
How did y'all get here?
Well, usually we came in either a packed car or in a pickup pulling a trailer with four club calves.
We did show at Houston and at Dallas and Sulphur Springs.
We had judging teams that went to Lubbock and West Texas State for competition and Roundup then down here in Stephenville.
Those were the towns that hosted many of these teams and that's where you got exposed to the world is when you went to a livestock show with an animal or went on a judging
trip with the team.
Do you remember your first visit ever to College Station?
Yeah I do.
When I got into beekeeping in 1947 I had kept bees and I got an invitation to speak at the Texas Beekeepers Association meeting November 1950.
My mama put me on a train at

Childress and I rode the train all day we stopped at Hearn about it was just getting dark and that's where you ate we had eaten lunch at Dallas and we ate supper at Hearn arrived here at the college station I guess you would call it the ticket counter cause when I stepped out
There was just a whole bunch of planks, like a patio, and down at the end was a little small shed.
It was dark.
Wasn't a soul in sight.
I didn't know what to do.
And about that time, Dr. F.L.
Thomas stepped out from behind that, I guess it was a ticket counter,
and I that's was my first trip to A&M and the meetings were held over at the Y and that was before the MSC was built.
What was your impression of A&M as a result of that visit?
Well I really didn't see much of the campus then
Where I got an impression of the campus was coming to 4-H Roundup, the state Roundup, where kids, probably 800 or 900 back then.
I think there's around 3,000 or 4,000 that come now.
But that's where we got to, usually came down on the judging team.

and we got to see the animals of classes met a few people but they kept us real busy so we couldn't get in trouble and were people friendly did that make did you get any I didn't have enough yes we met mostly the faculty people like Fred Elliott that for years did the barbecuing for roundup and John Box and

John E Hutchison Director of Extension and Floyd Lynch who was responsible for the 4-H programs in Texas back then but they had our activities so tightly scheduled that we primarily enacted with people over in Animal Science when it was judging and giving our reasons and that kind of thing but I really didn't know any of them until I came down here as a freshman
In fact, I didn't realize that A&M was all military and all mail when I got here in the summer of 55.
I figured it out.
I came down here because I wasn't sure that I could pass college work coming out of a small high school.
And I think Mom and Dad felt like that I needed to get out of there.

so i came down on monday after i graduated high school on friday so you came you began in the summer yes uh what did you how did you get here describe that trip how'd you get here what'd you bring well i got here probably like most aggies do back then i uh packed

What I needed, a couple pair of jeans and some underwear and a suit and a pair of tennis shoes and a pair of boots and ironing board, iron and a rub board to do my clothes and shaving and toothpaste and toothbrush with those in a duffel bag and a footlocker.
Mama took me, she knew that the vet was coming down for a clinic.
But she took me out south side of town and told me, go to A&M and don't come home.
Did you hitchhike?
Yes.
But Mama, I'm sure, knew that the vet was fixing to go to a clinic down here because Curtis Thaxton, who was the vet there at Wellington, picked me up.
And I had a room.

had a job i roomed over at mall hamilton's right back of the campus area there at north gate and she was a mom of the i didn't know at the end but later on i figured it out j.w hamilton who was sheriff brazos county and i had a job in the entomology department just across the railroad tracks over there at the lab with neil randolph what did it pay 17 cents an hour
Of course, I worked nights during the week at the pharmacy where Lupo's is now.
And I can't remember, Black's was over at Eastgate.
I can't remember the name of the pharmacy, but I jerked sodas.
And then on weekends, I worked at the Phoenix Station where the chicken oil company is there, where Oak College and College of Maine come together.
And you had those jobs lined up before you got here?
Well, no, I got the drugstore job in the
I had the anemology job with Neil Randolph, and I spent the whole summer shelling vetch seed.
He had treated some plots to control vetch brookhead up at Greenville.
And so you rode with the vet all the way down here, and describe how you enrolled in those summer classes.
Well, we went on with Sabisa and stood in line and registered.
And you'd have to go over to the tables that were labeled English or math.
The departments had their tables.
And you'd start out, if you had a major, you'd start out with a schedule of courses that you were approved to take or should take.
Then you went to each one of the departments, and they figured if the class had filled up or not, what times you were going to take them.
Of course, during summer school, there wasn't any problem in getting the classes that you needed to take.
I took one course each semester.
I took math, which was trig, and that was an advanced course then.
And so how did you survive those courses?
Pretty well?
Yeah.
much better than I really thought I would.
The coursework turned out not to be that difficult, but I remained scared until I graduated.
And so you're here all summer taking course and working.
Did you go home at the end of summer school?
No.
Stayed?
Too far.
Too far.
and I didn't have a car.
So I just, when I came in May, the first time I went home was Christmas.
Who did you, how did you make some friends?
Mostly where I was working, out at the lab.
That's where I met people and then at church.
Where did you go to church?
A&M United Methodist Church.
Back then it was College Station Methodist Church.
Describe that congregation in those years.
It was made up mostly of faculty and students.
The thing that always impressed me was the fact that nearly all of A&M's presidents back then were members of that church.
Including?
Earl Rudder, Jarvis Miller, Williams, Dr. Williams.
Was Harrington?
No, Dr. Harrington was not.
Gilchrist?
No.
Bolton?
No.
And you had gone to church then at home, so this was not a... Did you go on Sunday nights, or was there a...
There was NYF, or Wesley Foundation.
And they served supper?
Yes.
I said I went.
And you made some friends there.
Yeah.
Okay.
then describe the beginning of the fall and the core and all of those realities?
Well, it was mentally and physically demanding.
Of course, the thing that really impressed me was the fact, in retrospect, was what it cost to go to school here.
I believe that because I paid all of my expenses working

that first summer 17 cents an hour and in September I got a raise I got 25 cents an hour and that was back then big money uh I think most of the staff made 27 cents an hour but anyway uh because being in the Corps and they furnished so much of your uniforms and uh tuition and books really weren't that expensive and if even at 17 cents an hour if you worked
full-time in the summer, you could pay your bills.
I worked half-time.
I worked 20 hours during the semester, fall and spring semester, but I worked full-time in the summers.
Alright, so you were put in what outfit?
B-triple-A.
What was the nickname of that outfit?
B-triple-A.
They were extremely formal.
Two of the four years that I was in BAAA, we won the General Moore Award, which was the elite outfit on campus.
And it was based on academics, intramurals, military drill.
You got points for most of the activities.
So best all around outfit.
Yes.
So it was a good unit.
And I got some good training and a lot of hazing.
I didn't miss my daddy's whoopings when I got here.
Where did, where were y'all quartered?
We swapped from the Sbisa area to the Duncan area every other year.
So we were in dorm 17 when we were over in the Duncan area, the one backed by the USDA building.
We were in six and eight
the two years that we were over in the Sabisa area.
So now this is the fall of, you're a freshman in the fall of 1955.
Korean War is over.
Just ending.
Describe how you were introduced to all of the routine of the Corps and the dormitory and all that.
Well it was, it was very formal.
They all, you had the CO,
and the first sergeant you had a week you got down here a week before everybody else did and we took some tests and I never did I don't remember whether these were comparable to an ACT or an SAT
But one of the first things we did was go over to Sabisa and spent most of the whole day.
I think they actually, we were over there at 8, and about 8.30 we started taking tests.
And I don't know what those were for because I never had anybody ask me other than where I graduated.
I don't even remember submitting grades or anything.
If you had enough to pay your tuition, you could get an A&M.
Now, there were several things that worked against you staying here.
There were 43 in our freshman outfit, 43 freshmen.
Midterm, there were 27 of us left.
And I believe there were nine or 11 that graduated eventually, not in four years, but eventually graduated out of that
As you look back on those numbers and those people, about how many of them fail, left, because academically they couldn't do the work?
At that point in time, because a number of factors contribute to that.
One is maturity.
But certainly the lifestyle here was not what fit the expectations of a number of people.
I know the freshman next door to Fish Van Zant and I, and Joe Van Zant was from Wheeler, and he and I roomed together as freshmen.
And we had a Bill Cleland and a Fish Ryan Patterson.

who came out of uh Bel Air and Houston both of them ex brilliant individuals Bill majored in uh modern uh foreign languages then it's modern language now and physics and uh he's now with I think he's retired but he is uh for years he's been with Princeton and does uh

uh super atomic collision research spent a lot of time over in France and uh was just excited about coming home when the thing was up and going and the physics profession had invested so much in that he thought he might come home but anyway uh Bill and Ryan were
next door and Bill graduated as valedictorian in our class in 59.
Ryan, I watched him cry many, many nights after sophomore chewed him out.
He was extremely sensitive.
He went to Rice.
He transferred after his first semester here at Rice and he was valedictorian at Rice.
Well, what my question really is,
about what portion went?
About half of those flunked out.
Okay.
Several reasons, but about half of them flunked out.
The other just left because of the hazing, and they weren't going to tolerate being treated like that, and it just, they couldn't handle that.
It wasn't to their liking.
It didn't match their personality, their expectations, so they left.
So A&M had a way of
controlling the population here, it isn't handled like it is today.
Describe how you and your old lady got acquainted and how y'all
Well, we knew each other in high school because we showed together.
Joe was off a ranch up near Wheeler, and we knew each other and asked to be together.
I got in B-triple-A because of a cousin of mine who was a senior in 55.
Yeah, 55.
Recommended.
I didn't know anything about outfits or units.
Most of the freshmen were just put in a unit.
But if you had a request, it would be considered.
Describe the routine that first fall in that outfit, a typical day of classes.
Well, the thing that you had to get used to down here that I had the greatest difficulty getting used to is the weather.
Coming from the panhandle, there's no air conditioning.
And over at Ma Hamilton's, she had eight bedrooms, four on each side of the hallway upstairs.
And there was someone in each bedroom.
The bedroom was just a small room, probably 14 by 16 in size, had a bed in it, had a lavatory to wash your face in it, and had a chair and a desk.
in the restroom was at the end of the hall to take a bath or to use a pot.
But I got down here and nearly died coming out of a dry, low humidity area.
Like I found out the temperatures weren't that high but I couldn't sleep at night.
And I'd go down and take a cold shower
come back to my room and lay down in bed wet and naked.
And I could sleep until I'd dry off and start sweating again.
And then I'd wake up.
Got no sleep that first summer.
You get used to it after a while, but it takes a while.
But as a freshman, every bit of your time is very tightly scheduled, including study time.
Everybody knows everywhere that you're supposed to be and at what time.
Your Saturdays were, Saturday mornings we went to class, but Saturday afternoons we spent on the grill field working off the hours of bull ring.
Go through the routine of a weekday.
What time did you get up?
What did you do at what hour?
Go from getting up to going to bed.
I can't remember what it's called, but the whistle blew about 6 o'clock in the morning.
You had about 20 minutes to get up, shave, get dressed, and then we'd fall out in front of the dorms in units.
You were checked to make sure that your shoes were polished and all your brass was polished and that you were dressed and looked sharp.
Then we marched to the dining hall, either Duncan or Sabisa.
Freshmen of course stood at a brace and served everybody else.
And if you were lucky,

they all of the seniors and then juniors and then sophomores would leave and you would get what food was left on the table and you went to class and being in a science I had labs so most of the time I was in class from eight until five and then at five you got back to the dorm and we had intramurals something was going on

throughout the entire school year and you participated in swimming or wrestling or horseshoes or washers throw or basketball or flag football or golf or whatever came back at lunch you fell out at 12 o'clock marched over to

the dining hall and served the upperclassmen and then you went back to the dorm and always remember I always wondered what a chocolate eclair really tasted like and I had to wait until I was a sophomore to find out.
But it was a very regimented existence.
Alright then after supper was it always back to your room?
7 o'clock CQ lasted till 10.
And you, unless you had a pass or a permit, you were at your desk supposedly studying.
The only thing you could get up for is to go to the restaurant.
What did you and your buddy, where did you and your buddies go to escape that?
Let's say you had an hour in the day that was not scheduled.
Where could you go hide out to?
I had so many class hours, we would go to the MSC or we'd go to the church, the Wesley Foundation.
Bob Walker told me that's where he discovered the Church Christ.
He's a very, very active member of the Church Christ.
One of his close friends, a roommate I think it was, took him over there and that was a place where the sophomores wouldn't bother him.
I guess that I was just too slow and too dumb to figure all that out.

But I was in class most of the time and I think that's probably the reason I didn't have, I know I always envied the business majors because they went to class in the morning and then they took naps in the afternoon if they could keep the sophomores out of the room.
But I spent most of the time in class.
All right.
During the day.
Describe some of that hazing that freshman year.
Some of the routine.

Well, every time you turned around, somebody was having you hit a brace and telling you to do something or you were always busy taking care of sophomores, juniors, and seniors, whether it was shining shoes or what have you.

when you didn't do things well enough then you got a good harsh talking to after CQ and you'd get they'd get you in a room and spell out for you what you're supposed to do and how you're supposed to do it and you you had to be able to kind of grin inside you didn't dare grin on the outside
and just let that run off because it was constant.
All right, how often did the board get used?
Probably about once a week.
For what kind of evils?
Well, at halftime you had no idea what you'd done.
It was just for good bull.
But it didn't take much.
Usually though on those situations they were playing games and having fun.
That was not a form of discipline.
Mocking bull ring on Saturday afternoon was discipline.
They gave you demerits, wrote them out, signed them, and then it worked up through the process and then you had to work those hours off.
They'd give you demerit for not making your bed right.
for failing to shine your shoes, for being late falling out for lunch or for a drill or for marching at the game or what have you.
So, those were just experiences that you.
And the bull ring was where?
Over behind Duncan.
Behind Duncan?
Where they used to build the bonfire, where the press is now in the parking lot.
Yeah, yeah, okay.

all right um let's see uh chow hall routine um what was what was a fish duty what what duty did a fish have in the dining hall well you made sure that uh all the plates were full of course all the tables were served by uh cadets anywhere from freshmen to seniors and uh you made sure that the uh
tea glasses, coffee.
You just made sure that they had food and drink.
What was your, in those years, what were your favorite and your unfavorite Aggie foods?
Well, as a freshman, I would love to have tried a chocolatey Claire.
But I didn't find, we complained about the food.
But I gained weight.
I came here weighing about 124 pounds and at the end of my freshman year I took golf and weightlifting as my PE courses.
Back then, that first week you had to swim

back four times the length of the pool and if you couldn't you PE was swimming I guess the goal was make sure every Aggie could swim because that's what they insisted on and the least favorite probably was scrambled eggs because they nearly always were watery but most of the food you complain about but
It was nutritious and it was good.
I don't remember having a problem with food.
Were you introduced to any new foods at A&M?
Anything that you were not accustomed to?
Yeah, chocolate eclairs.
I'd never seen one.
I got half of one one time after everybody had left, but that's what I really enjoyed as a sophomore and a junior and a senior was
Did you and your buddies ever smuggle food back to the dormitory?
Under your shirt?
Yeah, that's the only way.
You grabbed it as you left and hurried to class.
That's about the only way that you've got food, except on weekends.
We got, because a lot of the seniors and juniors would be gone on weekends, so that's when we got to eat at a normal pace and got actually some real food.
Share with this machine some of the chow hall slang for foods that you remember.
Of course, bread was dough.
Ah, yes.
